BARTONELLOSIS - PERU (LIMA PROVINCE) (03)
***************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
[1]
Date: Tue 26 Sep 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Living in Peru, News [edited]
<http://www.livinginperu.com/news/2498>

Luis Suarez, chairman of the Directorate for Epidemiology at Peru's
Ministry of Health, called on the Peruvian population to remain calm
and discounted claims that the latest occurrences of bartonellosis,
also known as Peruvian wart or Carrion's disease, has reached
epidemic proportions.
Suarez stated that the sandfly responsible for the infections does
not exist in the capital of Lima and that the disease cannot be
transmitted from one person to another. He gave assurances that if
the necessary sanitary precautions are taken seriously, spreading of
the disease will be prevented.
He explained that bartonellosis is an endemic disease that stems from
the pre- Inca era and that since 1998, individual infections have
increased in some parts of Peru. The last time the Health Ministry
declared an epidemic was in 2004, after more than 7000 cases were treated.
Suarez emphasized that so far this year [2006], 4200 cases have been
registered. Unfortunately, he said, a vaccine against infection does
not exist, but effective individual treatment can avoid fatal consequences.
He also said that the transmitting insect does not bite before
sundown, and the typical symptoms do not appear until weeks after the
incubation period, which can be up to 2 months.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
